In all his available three works, Suryadeva styles himself as a triskandhárthavid, 'knower of the three branches of Jyotişa', viz., Ganita (Siddhanta), Horā and Samhita. The statement is exemplified by his commentaries on the Aryabhatīya, Laghumānasa and Mahābhās kariya-vyākhyā on Ganita (Siddhānta), Jātakapaddhati on Horā and Mahāyātra on Samhita. 
The personal deity whom Suryadeva worshipped appears to he Lord Krsna whom he invokes as 'the effulgence that is at the base of the creation, sustenance and destruction of the universe', at the beginning of his commentary on the Jatakapaddhati, in the verse : 
अगदुदयस्थितिसंहतिकारणमविकारि सचिवानन्दम् । 
श्रीमत् तत् कृष्णाख्यं तेजो मे हृदि सदा स्फुरतु ।। He pays obeisance to Lord Kļşņa in his form as the charioteer of Arjuna on the battle-field, wielding the whip and preaching the spiritual doctrine of the Gitā, at the beginning of his Laghumānasa vyakhyā also. Cf. : 
अध्यात्मविद्यामुपदेशयन्तं दृढं प्रपन्नाय धनञ्जयाय । 
प्रतोदहस्तं प्रगृहीतरश्मि देवं प्रपद्ये वसुदेवसूनुम् ॥ 
He mentions Lord Krşpa, son of Devakī, also towards the close of his commentary on the Jätakapaddhatt of Śrīpati (c. A. D. 1039), where he hopes that, by the grace of that God, he would be able to comment also on the Khandakhadyaka (of Brabmagupta). Cf. idānīm Bhatta-Brahmaguptaksta-Khandakhadyakavyācikīrşā vartate / tam ca Krsko Devakīputraḥ parayişyari // 
